			<div id="mw-js-message" style="display:none;"></div>
						<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en"><span dir="auto">Colossus of Rhodes</span></h1>
			<div id="bodyContent">
								<div id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
								<div id="contentSub"></div>
												<div id="jump-to-nav" class="mw-jump">
					Jump to:					<a href="#mw-navigation">navigation</a>, 					<a href="#p-search">search</a>
				</div>
				<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><p><a href="/w/index.php?title=Template:About&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Template:About (page does not exist)">Template:About</a>
</p>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:182px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Rhodes0211.jpg" title="File:Rhodes0211.jpg">File:Rhodes0211.jpg</a>  <div class="thumbcaption">An artist's impression of the <i>Colossus of Rhodes</i> from the <a href="/w/index.php?title=Grolier_Society&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Grolier Society (page does not exist)">Grolier Society</a>'s 1911 <i>Book of Knowledge</i>.</div></div></div>
<p>The <b>Colossus of Rhodes</b> (<a href="/w/index.php?title=Template:Lang-grc&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Template:Lang-grc (page does not exist)">Template:Lang-grc</a>) was a <a href="/wiki/Statue" title="Statue">statue</a> of the Greek <a href="/wiki/Titan_(mythology)" title="Titan (mythology)">Titan</a> <a href="/wiki/Helios" title="Helios">Helios</a>, erected in the city of <a href="/w/index.php?title=Rhodes_(city)&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Rhodes (city) (page does not exist)">Rhodes</a>, on the Greek island of the same name, by <a href="/wiki/Chares_of_Lindos" title="Chares of Lindos">Chares of Lindos</a> in 280 BC. It is considered one of the <a href="/w/index.php?title=Seven_Wonders_of_the_Ancient_World&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Seven Wonders of the Ancient World (page does not exist)">Seven Wonders of the Ancient World</a>. It was constructed to celebrate Rhodes' victory over the ruler of Cyprus, <a href="/wiki/Antigonus_I_Monophthalmus" title="Antigonus I Monophthalmus">Antigonus I Monophthalmus</a>, whose son unsuccessfully besieged Rhodes in 305 BC. Before its destruction in <a href="/w/index.php?title=226_BC_Rhodes_earthquake&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="226 BC Rhodes earthquake (page does not exist)">the earthquake of 226 BC</a>, the Colossus of Rhodes stood over 30 meters (98.4&#160;ft) high,<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">[1]</a></sup> making it one of the tallest statues of the <a href="/wiki/Ancient_world" title="Ancient world" class="mw-redirect">ancient world</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">[2]</a></sup>
</p>
<div id="toc" class="toc"><div id="toctitle"><h2>Contents</h2></div>
